            "elaborated_requirement": "<think>**Developing Design Details**\n**Refining Regulation Approach**\n**Exploring Regulator Architectures**\n**Building Discrete Regulator**\n**Developing Regulator Scheme**\n**Developing Regulator Scheme**\n**Developing Regulator Scheme**\n**Developing Regulator Scheme**\n**Filtering Input Signals**\n**Establishing Voltage Reference**\n**Configuring Error Amplification**\n**Driving the Pass Transistor**\n**Implementing Output Filtering**\n**Adding Status Indication**\n**Testing Load Regulation**\n</think>\nThis design provides you with a highly reliable, low-cost discrete 5V regulated power supply circuit based on the KiCad 8 standard component library. To ensure component versatility and ease of procurement, this design abandons dedicated highly integrated power management chips and instead builds a classic linear regulation feedback control system entirely from basic general-purpose components. The entire circuit can be functionally divided into five core modules: input filtering and protection, precision voltage reference, error amplification and dynamic regulation, overcurrent protection monitoring, and output filtering and indication.\n\nAt the power input, the system uses a standard DC power jack as the input peripheral, accepting 9V to 12V of unregulated DC power. In the input path, a 1N4148 switching diode or similar small-signal diode is first used with supporting logic to build a basic reverse-polarity protection circuit, preventing damage to downstream components from reversed external power polarity. The power then passes through a hybrid filtering network composed of a large aluminum electrolytic capacitor and a 0.1μF multilayer ceramic capacitor; the electrolytic capacitor is responsible for smoothing low-frequency voltage fluctuations and providing transient energy reserves, while the ceramic capacitor is dedicated to filtering high-frequency noise on the supply line.\n\nThe core regulation control loop employs a classic LM2904 dual operational amplifier. The circuit uses a basic Zener diode in series with a current-limiting resistor to generate a stable reference voltage, which is fed to the non-inverting input of one of the LM2904 op-amp channels as the reference source. The final output of the power supply is proportionally sampled through a feedback divider network composed of high-precision metal film resistors and sent to the inverting input of the same op-amp. The op-amp serves as an error amplifier, comparing these two voltage signals in real time, and its output directly drives a pass transistor module formed by cascading a general-purpose 2N3904 small-signal NPN transistor with a medium-power NPN transistor. When the output voltage experiences minor fluctuations due to load changes, the op-amp rapidly adjusts the base drive current of the 2N3904 through a deep negative feedback mechanism, thereby dynamically regulating the conduction voltage drop of the main pass transistor and tightly clamping the final output voltage at a precise 5V level.\n\nTo enhance the safety level of the power supply, the design also fully utilizes the remaining second op-amp channel inside the LM2904, combined with a low-value current-sense resistor placed in series in the main path, to build a sensitive overcurrent monitoring module. Should the load experience a short circuit or the current exceed the safety threshold, this op-amp will rapidly flip its output and forcibly pull down the control level of the main pass transistor through another 2N3904 transistor, implementing current limiting and cutoff protection.\n\nAt the power supply output, the system uses standard 2.54mm pitch terminal blocks or pin headers as output peripherals for convenient connection to subsequent load circuits. The output side is also paralleled with aluminum electrolytic capacitors and ceramic capacitors for secondary decoupling and filtering to improve load step transient response characteristics. Additionally, a light-emitting diode with a corresponding current-limiting resistor is placed in parallel on the output path as the most intuitive indicator of normal 5V power supply operation. The entire design can complete schematic capture and PCB footprint matching entirely based on the classic component library built into KiCad 8, without the need to import complex third-party component models, making it highly suitable as a reference design for higher education experiments, industrial auxiliary power supplies, or basic electronic prototypes.",
