            "elaborated_requirement": "<think>**Exploring Sallen-Key Design**\n**Finalizing Sallen-Key Design**\n**Refining Sallen-Key Components**\n**Designing Sallen-Key Circuit**\n**Designing Sallen-Key Filter**\n**Refining Sallen-Key Design**\n</think>\nThis design aims to create a high-reliability second-order Sallen-Key active low-pass filter with a cutoff frequency precisely set to 1 kHz on the KiCad 8 platform. The core active device of the circuit is the classic and versatile dual operational amplifier LM2904, which has native support in the standard component library, and its bandwidth and slew rate fully meet the analog signal conditioning requirements for the 1 kHz frequency band.\n\nIn the critical filtering network section, to ensure the accuracy of the 1 kHz cutoff frequency and good temperature stability, the frequency-setting resistors are all selected with 1% tolerance metal film resistors, while the core capacitors that determine the filtering characteristics are strictly selected from C0G or NP0 dielectric ceramic capacitors to avoid the effects of voltage bias and temperature drift on the frequency response curve.\n\nIn terms of input/output peripheral and interface planning, the test signal is introduced through standard 2.54 mm pin headers or SMA RF connectors. The input is first configured with a small-value series resistor as basic current-limiting protection, after which the signal enters the Sallen-Key RC network for high-frequency component filtering. The LM2904 op-amp primarily performs signal buffering and impedance transformation functions, using its high input impedance to avoid loading effects on the preceding filter network while providing very low output impedance to drive subsequent stages. At the op-amp output, a 50-ohm isolation resistor is placed in series to the output pin header, specifically intended to isolate unknown external capacitive loads and prevent high-frequency self-oscillation of the op-amp.\n\nAdditionally, the power input peripheral side also uses standard connectors, with a 1N4148 diode in series to implement basic power reverse-polarity protection. At the LM2904 power network nodes, a 10 μF general-purpose aluminum electrolytic capacitor is placed in parallel for low-frequency bulk energy storage, along with a 0.1 μF X7R dielectric SMD ceramic capacitor for high-frequency decoupling. These bypass components are placed close to the op-amp to absorb switching noise on the power rails, ensuring the purity of the op-amp output signal and the overall system stability.",
